SOQL Syntax Basics 

SOQL (Salesforce Object Query Language) looks like SQL but is deliberately narrower — no SELECT *, no arbitrary joins, no UNION. 
You must name every field explicitly, and you can only traverse relationships that are defined on the objects.
apexList<Account> accts = [
    SELECT Id, Name, Industry, AnnualRevenue
    FROM Account
    WHERE Industry = 'Technology' AND AnnualRevenue > 1000000
    ORDER BY Name ASC NULLS LAST
    LIMIT 100
];
The clauses you'll lean on: WHERE with AND/OR/NOT, IN/NOT IN (which pairs beautifully with a Set), LIKE with %/_ wildcards, ORDER BY … ASC|DESC NULLS FIRST|LAST, LIMIT, and OFFSET (capped at 2000). 
Date literals are a nice touch — you can write WHERE CreatedDate = TODAY or LAST_N_DAYS:30 instead of computing datetimes.
The killer feature is bind variables: prefix an Apex variable with : inside the query and it's safely interpolated, no string concatenation, no injection risk.
apexSet<Id> ids = new Set<Id>{'001...', '001...'};
String targetIndustry = 'Finance';
List<Account> results = [
    SELECT Id, Name FROM Account
    WHERE Id IN :ids AND Industry = :targetIndustry
];

