Relationship queries

This is the part with no direct SQL analog, and the direction matters a lot.
Child-to-parent (going "up") — use dot notation, up to 5 levels deep. Each record carries its parent, so a Contact can reach its Account and that Account's Owner:
apexList<Contact> contacts = [
    SELECT Id, LastName, Account.Name, Account.Owner.Email
    FROM Contact
    WHERE Account.Industry = 'Technology'
];
System.debug(contacts[0].Account.Name);          // traverse the loaded parent
Parent-to-child (going "down") — use a nested subquery, and you reference the child by its relationship name, 
which is usually the plural (Contacts, Opportunities) for standard objects and MyObject__r for custom ones:
apexList<Account> accts = [
    SELECT Id, Name,
        (SELECT Id, LastName, Email FROM Contacts WHERE Email != null)
    FROM Account
];
for (Account a : accts) {
    for (Contact c : a.Contacts) {              // nested child list
        System.debug(a.Name + ' -> ' + c.LastName);
    }
}
The two naming traps: for custom relationships, child-to-parent uses __r (e.g. Invoice__r.Name) while the field itself is __c; and the parent-to-child subquery uses the relationship name, 
not the object name — for a custom child it's typically Line_Items__r, not Line_Item__c. If a query complains about "didn't understand the relationship," it's almost always this.
