SOSL syntax

SOSL (Salesforce Object Search Language) is for full-text search across multiple objects at once — the thing SOQL can't do. 
Where SOQL says "give me records matching these field conditions on one object," SOSL says "find this text anywhere across these objects."
apexList<List<sObject>> searchResults = [
    FIND 'Acme*' IN NAME FIELDS
    RETURNING Account(Id, Name), Contact(Id, LastName), Lead(Id, Company)
];

Account[] foundAccts = (Account[]) searchResults[0];   // order matches RETURNING
Contact[] foundCons  = (Contact[]) searchResults[1];
The shape to remember: FIND 'searchterm' (in quotes, supports */? wildcards), an optional IN … FIELDS scope (ALL FIELDS, NAME FIELDS, EMAIL FIELDS, PHONE FIELDS), and RETURNING Object(fields) for each object you care about. 
It returns a List<List<sObject>> — one inner list per object in your RETURNING clause, in that same order.

When to reach for which: use SOQL when you know the object and are filtering on field values; 
use SOSL when you're doing a keyword search, especially across several objects, or searching text/long-text fields where SOSL's indexing is far more efficient than a bunch of SOQL LIKE '%...%' scans. 
In governor terms you get 100 SOQL queries vs. 20 SOSL searches per transaction.
